g and development, self-determination, equal value and just polity. This enables the authors to provide not only factual information on policies but also an in-depth understanding of the impact of welfare changes on the quality of life of Chinese people over the past three decades. A major strength of the book lies in its use of primary Chinese language sources, including relevant White Papers, central and local government policy documents, academic research studies and newspapers for each policy area. There are very few books in English on social policy in China, and this book will be welcomed both by academics and students of China and East Asian studies and comparative social policy and by those who want to know more about China's social development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPublic welfarezChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aNgok, Kinglun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPhillips, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z9783111196213oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978186134880740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847429599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847429599/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPc1995d2013